Demographic, military service, and clinical data comparing MRS-I and MRS-II are found in Table 1. Compared with MRS-I participants, those of the MRS-II cohort were younger, with lower predeployment CAPS scores, a higher prevalence of prior deployment, more time elapsed since the use of nicotine and caffeine, and a higher self-report of deployment-related stress (higher DRRI scores).
In MRS-I participants, the log-transformed LF:HF ratio was significantly associated with membership in the PTSD group such that higher LF:HF ratios at the predeployment visit were associated with new PTSD cases after deployment (OR, 1.63; 95% CI, 1.14-2.34; P = .008) (Table 2) (analyses of shrinkage and

